text:
Road violations in another EU country? The fine will arrive
05 Nov 2019, 22:45 by Pedro Pinto
Do you think that only road traffic offenses committed in Portugal can result in a fine? Do you know the European Vehicle and Driving License Information System (EUCARIS)?
With this system it is possible to identify and notify the owner of a registered vehicle in an EU country who has committed road traffic offenses in another Member State. The system has been in operation for some time.



According to information shared by GNR, the authorities of the various EU countries can identify and notify the holder of the vehicle identification document when some road traffic offenses are committed. For cooperation between authorities the EUCARIS platform is used.
Thus, the traffic enforcement authorities that discover a road traffic violation access the data on this electronic platform to notify the driver and consequently carry out the record.



What are the planned road violations

Violation of the maximum speed limits;
Failure to use or misuse the seat belt by the driver and passengers as well as other compulsory child restraint systems;
Failure to comply with the obligation to stop imposed by the red traffic light as well as failure to comply with the regulatory stop signal of the authorities competent to regulate and supervise the traffic and the indication given by the passing signal B2 - mandatory stop at the intersection ;
Driving under the influence of alcohol;
Driving under the influence of narcotic drugs, psychotropic substances or products with similar effects, disrupting physical, mental or psychological fitness;
Failure to use or misuse a helmet of an officially approved model by drivers and passengers of mopeds, motorcycles with or without sidecar, tricycles and quadricycles, provided that these vehicles are not fitted with a rigid body or at the same time rigid protective structure and seat belts;
Improper circulation on reserved roads, traffic lanes, special lanes, curbs and suppressed traffic lanes;
Continued use or handling of any equipment or device that may impair driving, such as hearing aids and radiotelephone handsets.

All information on the principles and rules for cross-border exchange of information related to road traffic offenses in a Member State of the European Union can be found in Law 49/2017.
